These two large branches of mathematics will be applied to the theory of elasticity in this book. This section is devoted to explaining how and where they are applied to give the reader perspective and motivation, and also to avoid disappointments. They are very useful subjects, but the reader must be warned that both take major efforts to master. It is wise to examine the possible benefits to see if this effort is relevant to one's needs.
Several examples of how geometric concepts are used in elasticity are discussed first. Perhaps the most obvious one is in rod and shell theory. Since a
